  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The article titled \"Baited reconstruction with 2D template matching for high-resolution structure determination in vitro and in vivo without template bias\" by Bronwyn A. Lucas, Benjamin A. Himes, and Nikolaus Grigorieff has garnered significant academic attention, evident from its 15 citations and notable mentions in prominent venues such as eLife and Nature Communications.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">This research, funded by reputable institutions including the Chan Zuckerberg Initiative and the Howard Hughes Medical Institute, underscores a commitment to advancing scientific understanding of structural biology. It has actively contributed to the ongoing discourse in the field, as indicated by its 15 citations from various journals, with a notable presence in bioRxiv and eLife.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The availability of a GitHub repository emphasizes the authors' commitment to open data and reproducibility. This repository serves as a vital software tool, promoting transparency and allowing other researchers to build upon their work. Notably, there have been 16 proven downstream reuses of the materials provided, indicating a healthy engagement with the research community.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Additionally, the article has demonstrated its impact within the academic landscape by being part of the contemporary conversation. The early sharing of a preprint allowed it to influence ongoing discussions, as evidenced by the 3 preprint citations that highlight its relevance to the field. This practice of open science aligns with modern research values and fosters immediate community engagement.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The presence of multiple open peer reviews, totaling five, enhances the transparency and credibility of the findings, allowing for thorough scrutiny and further discussion. The research has been recognized in various geographic contexts, particularly in the United States, Germany, and the United Kingdom, showcasing a broad international interest and validation within the scientific community.</p>",
